Therefore when you see a man bemoaning his hard case, that after death he shall either rot with his body laid in the grave or be devoured by flames or the jaws of wild beasts, you may be sure that his ring betrays a flaw and that there lurks in his heart a secret goad, though he himself declare that he does not believe that any sense will remain to him after death. He does not methinks really grant the conclusion which he pro- fesses to grant nor the principle on which hc so professes, nor does he take and force himself root and branch out of life, but all unconsciously imagines something of self to survive. For when any one in life suggests to himself that birds and beasts will rend his body after death, he makes moan for himself: he does not separate himself from that self, nor withdraw himself fully from the body so thrown out, and fancies himself that other self and stands by and impregnatcs it with his own sense. Hence he makes much moan that he has been born mortal, and sees not that after real death there will be no other self to re- main in life and lament to sels that his own self has met death, and there to stand and grieve that his own sels there lying is mangled or burnt. For if it is an evil after death to be pulled about by the devouring jaws of wild beasts‚ I cannot see why it should not be a cruel pain to be laid on fires and burn in hot flames, or to be placed in honey and stified, or to stiffen with cold‚ stretched on the smooth surface of an icy slab of stone, or to be pressed down and crushed by a load of earth above.
